HW2 Problem 12

(a) What is the probability that the other sibling is a girl? What assumptions are you making to perform this calculation?

Assumptions:

  1. The gender of children is independent and the probabiity of being a girl is 0.5.
  2. The person we meet is selected at random from all families with two children.

The unconditional sample space (\(\Omega\)) of families with two children, and the probabilities associated with each of the events (pairings of boy/girl combinations) is summarized below.

By telling us that one sibling is a girl, we elminate the possibility of the event \(\{B,B\}\) occuring. Thus, the probability that the other sibling is a girl is associated with the event \(\{G,G\}\).

\[\begin{eqnarray} P(\{G,G\}| \{B,B\}^c) & = & \frac{P(\{G,G\} \cap \{B,B\}^c)}{P(\{B,B\}^c)} \nonumber \\ & = & \frac{0.25}{0.75} \nonumber \\ & = & \frac{1}{3} \nonumber \end{eqnarray}\]

(b) Later in the conversation, it becomes apparent that she was discussing the older sibling.

Does this change your probability that the other sibling is a girl?

Yes. Using the sample space \(\Omega\) described above, we have a new conditional probability

\[\begin{eqnarray} P(\{G,G\}| \{B,B\}^c \cap \{G,B\}^c ) & = & \frac{P(\{G,G\} \cap \{\{B,B\}^c \cap \{G,B\}^c \})}{P(\{B,B\}^c \cap \{G,B\}^c)} \nonumber \\ & = & \frac{0.25}{0.5} \nonumber \\ & = & \frac{1}{2} \nonumber \end{eqnarray}\]

HW2 Problem 13

(a) Does this new information about one of the other prisoners give prisoner C any more information about his sentence?

  • P(C is let free | new information) = P(C is let free) implies that the new information give C no information about his sentence.
  • Let \(W\) be the even that the warden tells prisoner \(C\) that \(A\) is to be executed. Denote \(X,Y,Z\) as the events that \(A,B,C\) are to be let free, respectively.
  • Assume equal probabilties for each prisoner.

We first calculate \(P(W)\), then we use Bayes Rule to compute \(P(Z|W)\).

\[\begin{eqnarray} P(W) &=& P(W|X)P(X) + P(W|Y)P(Y) + P(W|Z)P(Z) \nonumber \\ &=& 0 \times \frac{1}{3} + 1 \times \frac{1}{3} + \frac{1}{2}\times \frac{1}{3} \nonumber \\ &=& \frac{1}{2} \end{eqnarray}\] \[\begin{eqnarray} P(Z|W) & = & \frac{P(Z \cap W)}{P(W)} \nonumber \\ & = & \frac{P(W|Z)P(Z)}{1/2} \nonumber \\ & = & \frac{(1/2)(1/3)}{1/2} \nonumber \\ & = & \frac{1}{3} \\ & = & P(Z) \end{eqnarray}\]

The new information gives C no information about his own sentence.

(b) The warden offers to let prisoner C switch sentences with the other prisoner whose sentence he has not identified. Should he switch?

Yes, he should switch.

Calculate \(P(Y|W)\). If \(P(Y|W) > P(Z|W)\), prisoner \(C\) should switch.

\[\begin{eqnarray} P(Y|W) & = & \frac{P(Y \cap W)}{P(W)} \nonumber \\ & = & \frac{P(W|Y)P(Y)}{1/2} \nonumber \\ & = & \frac{(1)(1/3)}{1/2} \nonumber \\ & = & \frac{2}{3} \nonumber \end{eqnarray}\]

Thus, prisoner C should switch.

nsim <- 1000; set.seed(10312) 
ps <- LETTERS[1:3]
## first two columns are prisoners set to be executed
exec <- t(replicate(nsim, sample(ps)))
## who is the other prisoner whose sentence he has not identified
tell <- ifelse(exec[,3] == "C", sample(ps[1:2], size=1), exec[,3])
## never switch
(psurv_no_switch <- mean(exec[,3]=="C"))
## [1] 0.337
## always switch
(psurv_switch <- mean(exec[,3] == tell))
## [1] 0.663

HW2 Problem 14

(a) What is the sensitivity and specificity of the CMMS test using the 20 cutoff?

  • Let \(+\) and \(-\) be the events that the CMMS test is positive or negative, respectively.
  • Further let \(D\) and \(D^c\) as the event that an individual has the disease, respectively.
  • Then for a cutoff of \(\leq 20\) we have
    • Sensitivity = \(P(+|D) = \frac{12}{16} = 0.75\).
    • Specificity = \(P(-|D^c) = \frac{34}{46} = 0.74\).

(b) Create a plot of the sensitivity by (1 - specificity), which is the true positive rate versus the false positive rate for all of the cut-offs between 0 and 30. This is called an ROC curve.

See Figure below.

## add in a 0 cut-off not in the data table
dat <- data.frame("score" = seq(0,30,by=5),
                  "No" = c(0,0,0,3,9,16,18),
                  "Yes" = c(0,2,1,4,5,3,1))
nLevels <- nrow(dat)

sens <- spec <- rep(NA, nLevels)
for(i in 1:nLevels){
    test_pos <- dat[1:i,-1,drop=FALSE]
    test_neg <- dat[-c(1:i),-1,drop=FALSE]

    sens[i]  <- sum(test_pos$Yes)/sum(dat$Yes)
    spec[i]  <- sum(test_neg$No)/sum(dat$No)
}

plot(1-spec, sens, ylab="Sensitivity", xlim=c(0,1),ylim=c(0,1),
     xlab="1-Specificity", main="ROC Curve for CMMS", type='l')

(c) Graph the positive predictive value as a function of the prevalence of AD.

Do the same for the negative predictive value.

Using the cutoff of \(20\) sated in the problem, and the formula

\[PPV = P(D|+) = \frac{P(+|D)P(D)}{P(+|D)P(D) + P(+|D^c)P(D^c)}\]

we create the graph below.

p    <- seq(0,1,len=100)
sens <- 0.75; spec <- 0.74
PPV  <- sens*p/(sens*p + (1-spec)*(1-p))

plot(p, PPV, xlab="Prevalence", ylab="PPV", main="", type='l')
